{{EngvarB|date=May 2018}} {{Use dmy dates|date=May 2018}} {{Infobox interbank network | name = EcoCash | logo = | area = [[Zimbabwe]] | members = [[Econet Wireless]] | atm = | foundation ={{start date and years ago|2011|09|29}} | owner = [[Econet Wireless]] | website =[https://www.ecocash.co.zw/ Homepage] }}
'''EcoCash''', is a [[mobile banking|mobile phone-based money transfer]], financing and [[microfinance|microfinancing]] service, launched in 2011 by [[Econet Wireless]], for its customers in Zimbabwe.<ref name="One">{{cite web| url=http://www.thezimbabwean.co/2011/09/eco-cash-launch-date/ | title=Eco-cash launch date |access-date=11 May 2018 | date=22 September 2011 |newspaper=''The Zimbabwean'' | author=Business Reporter |location=Harare}}</ref><ref name="Two">{{cite web|url=https://www.techzim.co.zw/2011/09/econet-announces-the-launch-of-ecocash/ |title=Econet announces the launch of EcoCash |access-date=11 May 2018 |location=Harare | date=29 September 2011 |publisher=Techzim.co.zw |author=Staff Writer}}</ref> The company's headquarters is in the Econet Wireless Building in [[Borrowdale, Harare|Borrowdale]], a suburb of [[Harare]], the largest city and capital of Zimbabwe.<ref name="Three">{{cite web|date=11 May 2018 |publisher=EcoCash Zimbabwe |url=https://www.ecocash.co.zw/contact |title=EcoCash Zimbabwe: Head Office |access-date=11 May 2018 |location=Harare | author=EcoCash}}</ref>
Econet allows users to deposit, withdraw, transfer money and pay for goods and services, including utility bills, from a mobile handset. Users can also buy pre-paid airtime or data bundles for themselves or others. Users can also redeem stored mobile money for cash. A fee for each service is deducted directly from the account stored on the mobile phone and accessed using a [[Personal identification number|PIN]].<ref name="Five">{{cite web|access-date=11 May 2018|url=https://www.ecocash.co.zw/about |title=EcoCash Zimbabwe: About Us |date=11 May 2018 |publisher=EcoCash Zimbabwe |author=EcoCash |location=Harare}}</ref> Users can deposit and withdraw money, transfer money to other users, pay bills including water, electricity, cable, satellite and school fees, purchase airtime, and transfer money between the service and a regular bank account.<ref name="Five"/> The service can be used from branches of [[ZimPost]].<ref name="Two"/>
As of November 2017, EcoCash was reported to have 6.7 million registered users<ref name="Six"/>, compared with 2 million conventional bank account holders in the country.<ref name="Six"/> It controlled 99.8 percent of the mobile money market in Zimbabwe at the time.<ref name="Six"/> During the first six years of existence, the service processed over $23 billion.<ref name="Six">{{cite web|title=EcoCash has processed over $23 billion since launch and that’s not the only impressive figure | url=https://www.techzim.co.zw/2017/11/ecocash-processed-21-billion-since-launch/ |access-date=11 May 2018 |date=10 November 2017 |first=Leonard |last=Sengere |publisher=Techzim.co.zw | location=Harare}}</ref> In 2017, Zimbabwe's Gross Domestic Product was valued at US$7.5 billion.<ref name="Seven">{{cite web|url=http://zimbabwe.opendataforafrica.org/nwnfkne/world-gdp-ranking-2017-gdp-by-country-data-and-charts |title=World GDP Ranking 2017: GDP by country: GDP, Current Prices: Source: IMF: World Economic Outlook (WEO) Database, April 2018 |date=28 April 2018 |access-date=11 May 2018 |publisher=[[International Monetary Fund]] (IMF) |author=IMF |location=Washington, DC}}</ref>
