{{Infobox person | honorific_prefix = | name = Samuel Garbett | honorific_suffix = | image = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = 1717<!-- {{Birth date|1717|MM|DD|df=y}} --> | birth_place = | death_date = {{Death date|1803|12|05|df=y}} <!-- {{Death date and age|1803|12|05|1717|MM|DD|df=y}}--> | death_place = | death_cause = | resting_place = [[St Philip's Cathedral, Birmingham|St Philip's, Birmingham]] | resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline}} --> | monuments = | residence = [[Birmingham]], [[England]] | nationality = | education = | occupation = Industrialist | known_for = | notable_works = | religion = | spouse = | children = | parents = | relatives = [[Charles Gascoigne]] (son-in-law) }}
'''Samuel Garbett''' (1717– 5 December 1803<ref name="ODNB">R. H. Campbell, ‘Garbett, Samuel (1717–1803)’, Oxford Dictionary of National Biography, Oxford University Press, 2004 [http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/40491, accessed 29 July 2012]</ref>) was a prominent citizen of [[Birmingham]] England, during the [[industrial revolution]], and a friend of [[Matthew Boulton]]. Historian [[Carl Chinn]] argues<ref name="Chinn">{{Cite journal | title = Friend of freedom and city's industry | journal = Birmingham Mail | last = Chinn | first = Carl | accessdate = 2012-07-29 | date = 2010-01-23 | url = http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-217267747.html |via=[[HighBeam]] |subscription=yes}}</ref> that he:
{{Quote|stood alongside Boulton as one of the key figures responsible for Birmingham's rapid expansion into one of the world's leading industrial towns.}}
Garbett's education extended:
{{Quote|[no] further than writing and accounts; but he was a man of great acuteness of genius and extent of understanding.<ref name="Carlyle">[[Alexander Carlyle]], autobiography, cited by Chinn</ref>}}
Garbett was employed by a London merchant named Hollis, as his agent for purchasing goods in Birmingham.<ref name="Chinn" /> In that role, he came:
{{Quote|into notice and rank among his townsmen; and the more he was known, the more he was esteemed.<ref name="Carlyle" />}}
He married Anne Clay (d. 1772) of [[Aston]] in August 1735.<ref name="ODNB" />
He then made his fortune as a merchant in his own right, before entering partnership with Dr [[John Roebuck]] to set up a laboratory in Steelhouse Lane where [[precious metal]]s were refined and [[assay]]ed; a manufacturing centre for [[sulphuric acid]] in [[Prestonpans]] in 1749; and, with others, the [[Carron Iron Works]], in Scotland, in 1760,<ref name="Chinn" /> in which the two Birmingham men each held a 25% share.<ref name="ODNB" /> He also chaired, from January 1788, a Birmingham committee against the [[slave trade]].<ref name="Chinn" />
His eldest child and only daughter Mary married [[Charles Gascoigne]] in 1759, and in 1765 Gascoigne became a partner in the Carron works, having been manager of Garbett's nearby [[turpentine]] factory, Garbett & Co., since 1763.
Garbett was involved in the creation of [[Birmingham Assay Office]] in 1773,<ref name="Chinn" /> and was the first chairman of Birmingham's Commercial Committee, forerunner of successive [[British Chambers of Commerce|Birmingham Chambers of Commerce]],<ref name="Chinn" /> as was a member of the committee that raised funds to create [[Birmingham General Hospital]].<ref name="Chinn" />
He was declared[[bankruptcy|bankrupt]] in 1782.<ref name="Chinn" /> Boulton encouraged him to re-establish his business in Birmingham, which he did successfully.<ref name="Chinn" />
At his death in 1803, his estate was over £12,000, albeit with some creditors not discharged.<ref name="Chinn" /> He was buried at [[St Philip's Cathedral, Birmingham|St Philip's Church]] (later Birmingham's cathedral), where he had been a [[church warden]].<ref name="Chinn" /> Matthew Boulton wrote of him:
{{Quote|I have always found his principles unfailingly just, honourable and liberal.<ref>M. Boulton to W. Davies, 12 Dec 1803; Matthew Boulton MSS</ref>}}
Throughout his life, Garbett played a prominent part in local politics and affairs, including police proposals and the development of [[Birmingham Canal Navigations|Birmingham's canals]].<ref>John Money, ''Experience and identity, Birmingham and the West Midlands 1760-1800'' (Manchester, 1977).</ref> During the [[Priestley riots|Birmingham riots of 1791]], it was at his house in [[Newhall Street]] that the town and country gentry held their emergency meetings.<ref>TNA HO 42/19/109.</ref> His political lobbying in general, and correspondence with [[William Petty, 2nd Earl of Shelburne|Shelburne]] in particular, make him a significant figure in national politics.<ref>John Money, ''op.cit.''; John Norris, ''Shelburne and reform'' (London, 1963); T M Norris, "Samuel Garbett and the early development of industrial lobbying in Great Britain," ''The Economic History Review'', 10(3) (1958), 450-460.</ref>
